mb|1D|nt|The S hand has some flaws, like @hKQ doubleton ... but also some plus factors, like the @d109 so I'd open. There is some debate as to which suit to open with 4-4 minors. Traditional wisdom is to open 1@D, so that if you must you can rebid clubs. Modern style is to open 1@C, since you won't rebid a suit anyway, but will bid NT.|pg||
nt|Some top expert partnerships deliberately have no agreement, so they can do what feels right at the time, and their opps won't have an inference about minor suit length when they play 3NT. KR says this one worth 11,95. I open 1@D, so that if it goes 1d - 1s - dbl -, I can rebid 2@C|pg||
mb|p|nt|West should pass, hand not strong enough for a takeout dbl, and hearts not good enough for overcall.|pg||
mb|2D|nt|In SAYC, the raise to 2@D shows 6-9 or a bad 10 dummy points. This is worth about 9: you can count something for the doubleton club, but not the Queen as well. Another alternative is 1NT = 6-9 or bad 10 with no major but I don't like 1nt with @sxxx and @hAxx, those are not "good lead values". If partner has Queens or Jacks in those suits, better to play the NT from his hand.|pg||
mb|p|nt|Why doesn't East bid with 11 points? The answer is that East has 3 diamonds. Balancing is all about shape, not points.|pg||
mb|p|nt|S has no reason to bid|pg||
mb|d|nt|but now W should Dbl. The opps have a fit, increasing the chances that your side does as well, and it is very important to push them up a level when they find their fit and settle at the 2-level. West has already passed, and so he can show his shape now without his partner getting carried away. If West has few HCP, that's OK his partner will have a little more.|pg||
nt|The idea when it goes 1x p 2x p p ... both sides have about half the points so it is the player who is short in their suit who must bid ... that way if they're in a 4-3 fit, you can leave them there. I would do this (West's Dbl) at any vulnerability and any scoring except rubber bridge chicago style. It is just a losing proposition to let them have the 2-level in their 8+ fit.|pg||
mb|3D|nt|Now, North's question is: is he willing to defend vs. 2@h or 2@s, or will he compete to 3@D over them. If you are willing to compete to 3@D, you should do so immediately, don't give them the 2-level to find their fit, and then the 3-level to decide what to do. With what is most likely a 9-card or more diamond fit, I'd bid 3@D right away.|pg||
mb|p|nt|Note that East has no trouble passing this... The whole point of West's double was to push the opps to the 3-level, once that is accomplished, the bidding is done. If North had passed, East should bid @2h, cheapest 3-card major, giving them lots of room to keep on bidding. You could bid 2@S, as your better major, but I wouldn't go to the 3-level to try my Jxxx suit. What you're really hoping is that they'll bid again. So whatever you do, don't sit and squirm, and sigh, and look like you wish you didn't have to bid.|pg||
